<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,978,1765]" pageId="11" pageNumber="244">
<emphasis box="[199,305,1524,1549]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="244">Abdomen</emphasis>
: Abdominal tergum heavily sclerotized as in 
<figureCitation box="[817,900,1524,1549]" captionStart="FIGURES 39 – 43" captionStartId="13.[151,264,1648,1671]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,193,1626]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[151,1436,193,1629]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURES 39 – 43. Neomeschia queenslandensis, holotype female: 39, abdominal dorsum; 40, abdominal venter; 41, 42, ovipositor; 43, spermatheca." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/252250/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="244">
Fig. 
<number box="[869,900,1525,1549]" pageId="11" pageNumber="244" value="39.0">39</number>
</figureCitation>
; connexivum with dense punctures all over. All terga with faint punctures of varying size but more distinct on sides; punctures sparse on III. Scar between III–IV very small, IV–V of medium size, and V–VI widest, with suture curved more deeply from anterior to posterior scars. Abdominal sterna uniformly pale except for a submedian row on each side of fuscous spots in anterior half of each segment, particularly sterna V–VII (
<figureCitation box="[615,699,1668,1693]" captionStart="FIGURES 39 – 43" captionStartId="13.[151,264,1648,1671]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,193,1626]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[151,1436,193,1629]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURES 39 – 43. Neomeschia queenslandensis, holotype female: 39, abdominal dorsum; 40, abdominal venter; 41, 42, ovipositor; 43, spermatheca." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/252250/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="244">
Fig. 
<number box="[667,699,1669,1693]" pageId="11" pageNumber="244" value="40.0">40</number>
</figureCitation>
); finely densely punctate all over.
</paragraph>
